WELL: Nido Ranch 8H - Nido Ranch West Pad - 1H - Nido Ranch 8H
COMMENTS: The Assembly was run to drill the curve. It was a LDS motor in conjunction with a Hughes 306TS bit selection. The motor was set @ 2.25?.it drilled from KOP of 10248 and was pulled at 10447?. It was pulled projecting 21.65 angle and 207 azm. It yielded 12.7 in the first 100ft and 10.7 in the second 100?. The reason it was pulled was poor TF control and low ROP. It was very touchy with minimal WOB. It was erratic ob TF control with low ROP. A 100 pound diff spike would travel 360 degrees and then come back to origin. Decision was made to pOOH to inspect assembly. At surface the motor drain fine and exhibited minimum amount of slack and play. The bit was green and frded at 0-1-WT-N-X-I-NO-BHA. The assembly was run to drill the curve using an LDS motor in conjunction with a Hughes 306TS bit. The motor was set at 2.25? and drilled from the kickoff point at 10,248 to 10,447. Upon being pulled, the projection showed a 21.65? inclination and 207? azimuth. The assembly delivered a build rate of 12.7? per 100 in the first 100 feet and 10.7? per 100 in the second 100 feet. During the drilling process, there were five hard stalls. It was pulled due to poor toolface control and low (ROP). The assembly exhibited erratic TF behavior with minimal weight on bit (WOB), and a 100-pound differential pressure spike would cause the toolface to rotate 360? before returning to its origin. Given these performance issues, the decision was made (POOH) and inspect the assembly. At the surface, the motor drained as expected and exhibited minimal slack or play. The bit was graded as green, with a score of 0-1-WT-N-X-I-NO-BHA.

WELL: Nido Ranch 8H - Nido Ranch West Pad - 1H - Nido Ranch 8H
COMMENTS:
TD Section This run was smooth overall. The assembly successfully drilled surface hole from 80 ft to 3565 ft Total Depth, holding well in rotation and maintaining good control with an average yield while sliding between 6-10? per 100 ft. .

WELL: Nido Ranch 8H - Nido Ranch West Pad - 1H - Nido Ranch 8H
COMMENTS:
ROP - The BHA run did not achieve its objective of drilling out at 3,509 and reaching the Intermediate section TD. After drilling out the shoe track and beginning to drill in the Intermediate section, the assembly would only drill at a rate of 80-100 feet per hour with a maximum differential pressure of 350 PSI. After troubleshooting and washing, it was thought that a balled-up bit might be the cause of the low ROP. Following these actions, the ROP increased to 200 feet per hour, and the differential pressure rose from 350 to 750 PSI.
However, issues persisted when attempting the first slide. The assembly repeatedly acted as if it were wedging, making only 3 feet of progress before experiencing resistance again. This pattern continued throughout the slide, with overpull reaching up to 80,000 pounds over the string weight when picking up out of the slide. Returning to bottom, all differential pressure would drop off, and weight on the bit would stack out. To address this, a wiper trip was made. Upon returning to bottom, a successful slide was completed. However, while rotating down the remainder of the stand, the ROP again dropped significantly, from over 200 feet per hour down to just 20 feet per hour.
At this point, the decision was made to pull out of hole (TOOH) and inspect the BHA. At the surface, the mud motor showed minimal slack and play in the bearing section during the drain procedure. The bit was graded at 1-8-RO-S-X-I-NR-PR, with ringing out on the shoulders. Based on these observations, pick up a new Ulterra SP613.

WELL: Nido Ranch 9H - Nido Ranch West Pad - 1H - Nido Ranch 9H
COMMENTS: Stator Chunk This assembly drilled the curve section, kicking off at 10,311 and landing at 11,160. The motor yield throughout the run averaged 14.5? per 100, exceeding the plan, which was designed for 12? per 100. After landing, the assembly continued into the lateral until 13,843, at which point the decision was made to pull for a lateral assembly with a 1.83? motor setting and a stabilizer above the motor.Drilling parameters in the curve initially included a differential pressure of 350-450 PSI and a rate of penetration (ROP) of 30-40 feet per hour. Upon exiting the Anachoncho and entering the chalk, the formation cleaned up, allowing for higher differential pressures of 800-1,000 PSI and an ROP exceeding 150 feet per hour. In the lateral, the assembly averaged 700-800 PSI differential and tracked well in rotation, showing an overall tendency to build and drop slightly while turning left.At the surface, the motor drained tight with minimal play in the bearings. The bit was graded at 1-1-NO-A-X-1/16-RR-BHA, and two jets were found to be plugged with stator rubber

WELL: Nido Ranch 13H - Nido Ranch West Pad - 1H - Nido Ranch 13H
COMMENTS:
This assembly was run in at 5,876 to replace the previous one, which had chunked stator rubber and plugged the jets on the bit. It successfully drilled to TD without incident. In rotation, the assembly exhibited a drop of approximately 1 degree per 100, but after ramping up from a slide, it would build for 200-300. The motor yielded an average of 8-10 degrees per 100. Operational parameters included an average differential pressure of 800-900 PSI, rotary speed of 60 RPM, and weight on bit of 40,000 pounds. The maximum recorded temperature was 219?F.
At surface, the bit was graded as green, with a score of 1-1-NO-A-X-I-RR-TD. The motor drained as expected on the table, showing no signs of slack or play.
ADDITIONAL_COMMENTS: Assembly tracked well in upper portion of intermediate tangent. Assembly was slid 40 feet right of plan to accomodate AC concerns. Once around AC concerns assembly was steered back into hole direction holding azm but dropping inclination 0.5?/ 100. Upon attempting to slide in anacacho, once the bit to bend was buried, WOB would stack as differential was lost. Several attempts to slide were made resulting in hard stalls. With the assembly dropping inclination as it was and sliding being burdened, it was decided to TOOH for a fresh assembly. Upon out of the hole the motor shown no signs of weaking, had no slack in bearings, drained as it should, & had no wear on the pad. Bit graded @ 1/3/CT/G/X/3/WT/BHA

WELL: Nido Ranch 13H - Nido Ranch West Pad - 1H - Nido Ranch 13H
COMMENTS:
Stator Rubber - While drilling ahead and initiating a slide at 5,876 in the intermediate section of the 13H, the differential pressure spiked to 1,500 PSI, causing the stall assist to slow the pumps to half throttle. The pumps were killed, and the assembly was picked up off bottom while surface equipment was checked.  Nothing was found after slow pumps rates were done on all three pumps  Once the pumps were brought back to full rate, the pressure was recorded at 5,100 PSI, up from the previous 4,100 PSI. An attempt was made to resume sliding, but pressure continued to fall off, and off-bottom pressure settled at 4,600 PSI.
After returning to rotation, drilling continued down to 5,282, where a second pressure spike of 1,000 PSI occurred, reactivating the stall assist. Off-bottom pressure again read 4,600 PSI. At this point, the decision was made to trip out and inspect the assembly. At surface the motor bearing were tight, but when the bit was broke off thier was stator rubber plugging three of the jets. The bit graded 1-1.

COMMENTS: Change BHA This curve/ lateral assembly successfully ran from drill out of casing shoe at 8,245 to planned trip depth for lateral assembly at 14,014, utilizing a Ulterra U611S bit. Throughout the run, temperatures ranged from 170?F from drill out to 296?F in the lateral. Building the curve took longer than anticipated due to erratic TF?s when sliding but eventually cleaned up once transitioning into the eagle ford shale. Build rates suffered during the curve but were able to achieve a sufficient DLS in the eagle ford to land 8? low of the TL. The assembly maintained an average differential pressure of 400 psi building the curve & 800 psi drilling the lateral, with an average weight on bit (WOB) of 40,000 pounds and an average rotary speed of 75 RPM. The flow rate during the operation ranged between 500 and 700 GPM. The assembly predominantly held the planned trajectory in rotation. In slide mode, the motor achieved an average yield of 12? per 100. Upon inspection at the surface, the motor drained tight with no significant slack or play observed but did have signs of wear on the lower portion of the pad. The bit pulled worn more than usual for runs like it on previous wells and was graded at 2/2/LT/A/X/I/CT/BHA

COMMENTS:
The assembly successfully drilled the curve section, kicking off at 10,458 and landing at 11,276. The 2.12-degree motor performed efficiently, achieving an average yield of 14.0? per 100, exceeding the planned 12? per 100. After landing, the assembly continued into the lateral section, reaching 12,878 before being pulled in favor of a lateral assembly configured with a 1.83? motor setting and a stabilizer above the motor.
Drilling parameters in the curve section initially included a differential pressure of 350-450 PSI and an ROP of 30-40 feet per hour. Upon exiting the Anachoncho formation and transitioning into the chalk, the cleaner formation allowed for increased differential pressures of 700-800 PSI and an ROP exceeding 140 feet per hour. In the lateral section, the assembly maintained a differential pressure of 700-800 PSI, displaying an occasional aggressive build tendency, particularly beyond 91 degrees.
At the surface, the motor was inspected and found to be tight, with minimal play in the bearings. However, the kick pad was noted to be damaged, with a section missing in the area where it was built up. The bit was graded 1-2-CT-G-X-I-WT-BHA.

COMMENTS:
While drilling ahead in the lateral section at 17,810, the differential pressure suddenly dropped from 700 PSI to 100 PSI, and torque fell from 20k to 5k. The weight stacked out at 45k, and the ROP dropped to zero. Upon picking up, the off-bottom pump pressure returned to 5K psi, consistent with pre-incident levels. Attempts to set the assembly down in slide mode revealed no reactive torque. Based on these observations, the decision was made to TOOH. 

Upon decision to TOOH, the majority of circulating hours on the assembly was circulated after the failure circulating out gas, weighting up MW, & reaming back T/ bottom after failed attempt to TOOH.

At the surface, the mandrel was found extended approximately 8 inches, and the motor failed to drain, indicating a broken drive shaft. The bit was graded @ 3-1-BF-N-X-1/16-BT-DMF
.

COMMENTS: This Assembly was run to drill the curve utilizing an LDS 7.25 5/6 8.2 motor in conjunction with a Baker Hughes DD306TS bit selection. The motor was set @ 2.12?, drilled from KOP of 10,333?, and was pulled at 10445? projecting 11? inclination with a 330? azimuth. Motor yielded an 11.6 in the 32? of slide seen however the assembly exhibited erratic TF behavior with minimal weight on bit. (100 psi differential pressure spike would cause the TF to ?flop? 360? before returning to its origin & encountered 5 hard stalls.) Given these performance issues, the decision was made to TOOH and inspect the assembly. Upon reaching surface, the motor drained as expected, exhibited minimal slack, and minimal wear on the pad. The bit was graded @ 1/1/CT/S/X/1/NO/PR

COMMENTS: Planned - The assembly successfully finished drilling the curve section, landing at 11,215? on plan. The 2.12-degree motor performed efficiently, achieving an average yield of 13.5? per 100, exceeding the planned 12? per 100. After landing, the assembly continued into the lateral section, reaching 13,165 before being pulled in favor of a lateral assembly configured with a 1.83? motor setting and a stabilizer above the motor. Drilling parameters in the curve section initially included a differential pressure of 350-450 PSI and an ROP of 40-60 feet per hour. Upon exiting the Anachoncho formation and transitioning into the chalk, the cleaner formation allowed for increased differential pressures of 700-800 PSI and an ROP exceeding 120 feet per hour. In the lateral section, the assembly maintained a differential pressure of 750-850 PSI, displaying a build tendency, particularly beyond 91 degrees. At the surface, the motor was inspected and found to be tight, with minimal play in the bearings, & no wear on the kick pad. The bit was graded 1-1-CT-G-X-I-WT-BHA.

COMMENTS:
Chunk While tripping in the hole with BHA #5, a tight spot was encountered at 8,360. A string weight of 60k was set down on the bit but attempts to pick up resulted in the string hanging up. Pumps were brought online, registering 3,500 PSI at 400 GPM, indicating the bit was stuck and the motor had stalled. After pulling 80k over the string, it was successfully freed. The section was reamed out and cleaned before tripping in the hole to bottom at 13,165.
Once on bottom, the rate of penetration with the current assembly was 70-80 ft/hr. with only 300 PSI differential. In comparison, the previous assembly achieved a ROP of 150-180 ft/hr. A significant amount of stator rubber was observed returning over the shakers. Based on these findings, the decision was made to TOOH for assembly inspection. Upon out of the motor was already drained when atttemping to drain it, had no slack in bearings, & no wear on pad. Bit pulled green and was re-ran on BHA #6.

COMMENTS:
During the day on 12/30 the drilling had become progressively slower and slower. The diff was holding in strong, so it wasnt a sign the motor was getting weak but with the very low ROP we had concerns the bit was getting bad. They decided to keep drilling. When we made the connection at 17,443 MD and went back to drilling, ROP had almost doubled but now the torque was very erratic (25-16K). Looking at drilling parameters, we noticed that the driller was still running 35K on bit, but the hook load was now 247K while drilling. Before the connection the hook load was 260K with 35K on bit and after the connection we had 247K hook load with 35K weight on bit. Went over and talked to CoMan about how we had a bad rezero on bit weight. He told me that there?s no way to reset the hook load. I told him i understood that, but you can rezero the weight at any given point. He didnt grasp the fact that we were now running 48K on the bit weight with a 247K hook load. He told me not to worry about it. After watching the erratic torque for a while, I went back over and discussed possible bit damage and the possibility of damaging the motor with the erratic torque. I was concerned that the bit was coring with the excessive torque swings. I was told that i didnt know WTF i was talking about that we were in shale, and it couldnt core a bit. We continued to drill with high weight and extreme torque until 17,535 MD at that point we lost torque and the diff fell off slightly. At that point CoMan called and ask what was wrong. I explained it wasnt the motor because we could still get some diff when tagging bottom, but the bit was probably smooth and has probably been under gauge for a while.
Drilled 4208 ft. Motor pulled dry to the Bit and Had about a 1/8 Slack. Max Temp On Run 323 degrees. We stalled the Motor numerous Times w/ pressures reaching over a 1000 psi. Max Diff Drilling 1000 psi. Average Diff. was 800 psi. The Bit  had 2 missing jets and 5 Plugged jets and 4 chipped cutters. Bit graded 3-2

COMMENTS: Drilling ahead in the Intermediate section, we experienced several stalls while rotating, as well as one stall while sliding. Rotating at 842 GPM, 50 RPM, 80/hour at time of initial stalls. This was in the middle of the Navarro formation. Shortly after, ROP decreased to 40-50/hour, at which point different parameters were attempted in an effort to increase ROP. Higher ROP returned with original parameters within 200 of initial ROP decrease. In the hours following, more stalls were experienced with a severe decrease in ROP and rubber being observed coming over the shakers. Decision was made by engineer to continue drilling with decreased ROP to get through abrasive formation before POOH to RIH with a new motor/bit. Upon reaching Surface, motor showed minor visible wear to bearing stabilizer blades, 1/4 squat, and was already dry when attempting to drain. Bit was balled up. Once cleaned, it showed chipped cutters at nose and taper, as well as having 3 plugged jets.

COMMENTS: The objective of this BHA run was to TD Intermediate section. In this regard it was successful. ROP was limited by abnormal torque while rotating. Torque issues were somewhat mitigated by increasing Rotary RPMs, but we were still unable to reach and drill with desired WOB while rotating.  BHA showed a tendency to drop in Inclination in nudge through the Olmos formation, but showed an equally consistent tendency to build afterwards in the San Miguel formation. Experienced two stalls while sliding, oscillating at torque between 5K and 7K. Each time pump rate was reduced before picking up off bottom from stall. Upon reaching Surface, motor showed no squat in bearing section and drained strong. No external visible damage or wear to motor.Bit graded 1-2, as the damage seen was broken cutters on shoulder of bit.

WELL: BAPTIST FOUNDATION - HOSEK C 3H - DUNN, HOSEK, BAPTIST FOUNDATION PAD - Wellbore 1
ADDITIONAL_COMMENTS:
The purpose of this run was to spud, drill to and build 7.7? Tangent, and hold 7.7? Tangent to Surface casing point.
 Drilled to 754, at which point we started, built, and held Tangent. At 2,187 we increased GPM to 900 GPM and pumped a sweep. During the course of drilling that stand down after increasing GPM and pumping sweep, we experienced a constant and significant increase in SPP. After making a connection and kicking the pumps on, pressure showed to be 4,050 PSI off bottom with 800 GPM @ bit depth of 2,187, as where SPP off bottom was 1800 PSI @ 888 GPM @ bit depth 1,795.
 After swapping pumps and attempting varying GPM off bottom for troubleshooting purposes, decison was made to rotate one stand. Pressure no longer increased, but did remain very high around 4,000 PSI SPP at 780 GPM while drilling stand down. An attempt to slide at top of next stand was unsuccessful; toolface control was still easily attained, yet weight stacked with no ROP.
  Decision was made at this point to TOH and change BHA.
  Upon clearing rotary with bit, water was seen to be coming out of the jets, but when we attempted to drain motor, the motor was locked up and would not drain. No squat at bearing section, bit grade was 1-1.

WELL: BAPTIST FOUNDATION - HOSEK C 3H - DUNN, HOSEK, BAPTIST FOUNDATION PAD - Wellbore 1
ADDITIONAL_COMMENTS:
The objective of this run was to drill in Surface section of the well with Tangent to Surface casing point. We successfully reached this objective.
  Upon clearing rotary rable after run, motor was seen to have no visible exterior damage, 1/2 squat in bearing gap, and drained well.
  Bit graded 1-5 with no damage at nose, but significant wear at matrix on gauge rows.

WELL: DUNN - EDWARD HOSEK B 2H - DUNN, HOSEK, BAPTIST FOUNDATION PAD - Wellbore 1
ADDITIONAL_COMMENTS:
MWD tool begin to have erratic decoding and we were unable to log gamma and all other important information.  Tool was unable to pulse while drilling on bottom which caused the erratic decoding.  However, the MWD tool would populate surveys and decode at 100% off bottom.
  Decision made by client to TOH for MWD tool. Upon reaching surface, motor showed no exterior damage, had no significant squat at bearing section, and drained well. Bit graded 1-1.
PHASES: INT-1: INTERMEDIATE 1 / CURVE: CURVE / LAT: LATERAL

WELL: DUNN - EDWARD HOSEK B 2H - DUNN, HOSEK, BAPTIST FOUNDATION PAD - Wellbore 1
ADDITIONAL_COMMENTS:
The objective of this run was to TD Lateral section while staying in window as directed by geology as per client directive. We were successful in this objective.
 BHA showed a definite tendency to build throughout run. GPM used while drilling varied from 480 GPM to 630 GPM, depending on what lost circulation issues were being experienced at any given time.
  While TOH at TD, upon TOH to 4,964 (above Surface casing shoe), rig attempted to pump a slug, but couldnt pump through string. Rig continued to TOH wet for rest of trip.
  Upon clearing rotary, motor had no squat and no visible exterior damage. Float in motor was packed with LCM, but would actuate upon pressing plunger. Attempts to drain motor were unsuccessful; motor was locked up. Bit missing cutter at nose, as well as chipped cutters on gauge rows. Bit graded 2-2.

COMMENTS:

This run consisted of drilling out Surface casing equipment, drilling into Vertical to K.O.P., kicking off and drilling Curve, and drilling into Lateral section of the well. Motor yields experienced at kicking off Curve section exceeded 19?/100, necessitating increased lengths of rotation thorughout Curve.
  While drilling in Lateral section of well, after making connection we experienced greatly diminished ROP as well as torque spikes to 25K. Decision was made by client to TOH and change motor and bit.
  Upon reaching surface, Motor was seen to have a  significant gouge on bearing housing. Motor drained well with 3/8 Squat at bearing section.
  Bit was graded 3-8, with the nose and cone showing relatively minimal damage but shoulders worn deep into the matrix.

MWD_COMMENTS: Connection @ 21,246 MD Tool Flatlined w/ temp of 338?. Drilled 40 F/21,246  T/21,286 With Previous Parameters. No Sweeps Or LCM Was Pumped Prior To MWD Flatline. Pressure Was Unchanged At Flatline. While Circulating the Tool never synced back up. Changed out transducer, checked/ changed and isolated pumps w/ no change. Drilled 40 to 21,286 and tool showed no signs of pulses. Decision made to call the well at 21,286 MD.

COMMENTS:
While drilling ahead @ 3,334, we lost all torque and differential. We thought we possibly had a balled up bit. We pumped two nut plug sweeps and turned the rotary up to 80 RPM. while running 2-5K on weight on bit. We didnt see any results so the decission was made to POOH.
  When we got the BHA to surface there was no visable damage. The motor did not drain and the bit was green.

ADDITIONAL_COMMENTS: While drilling ahead motor took a hard stall and motor pressured up where we were unable to pump and had to dry ream F/16253-13478. Upon reaching  surface the shaft was broken and it appeared the bent sub had come unscrewed from the power section.
SURFACEFINDINGS: Motor had backed off at top of bent sub with shaft broken.

ADDITIONAL_COMMENTS: While drilling in lateral ROP and build rates fell off and decision was made to call TD when it quit drilling.ROP steadily declined over the last couple of stands but there was no iniccation of motor failure at the time. When tagging bottom differential and torque would increase but ROP would not. Upon reaching surface the motor appeared to have backed off at the top of the bent housing.
SURFACEFINDINGS: Motor was broke and backed out at bottom of power section at bent housing
TROUBLESHOOTING: Tried Re- zeroing and easing back to bottom

ADDITIONAL_COMMENTS:
The purpose of this run was to spud, drill in Surface section, build and hold 24.81? Tangent to Surface section TD. 
  Upon approaching Tangent Inc, well was observed to be building significantly in rotation. The trend of building in rotation consistently continued throughout the Tangent, at times upwards of 2.5?/100 DLS, with such constant frequency as to necessitate regular slides down to ameliorate build.
 Sliding was fairly straighforward, with the most noticeable challenge being sudden losses of differential and just as sudden returns of differential, likely due to sand stringers in formation.
  Upon clearing rotary, motor showed no visible exterior damage, had no significant play at bearing section.
  Bit graded 1-1.

BHA was a succesful one run curve and lateral. 

BHA had no visable damage when we got to surface. The motor drained good and had 2mm thrust.
PHASES: INT-1: INTERMEDIATE 1 / CURVE: CURVE / LAT: LATERAL

ADDITIONAL_COMMENTS:
The objective of this run was to drill out cement, Intermediate float equipment/shoe, land Curve, and continue on into Lateral section of the well.
 While drilling, BHA performed well with motor giving 19? to 23? MY consistently, allowing us to land Curve and drill in Lateral with minimal slide footage. We were also able to respond to target changes as needed. ROP started out 250/hour and by the last 1,000 of the run had decreased to 130/hour average. Gamma was 120 to 140 Gamma count up til 15,637, where we experienced a significant shift in Gamma count to 180 to 200. We drilled to 16,206 at which point we TOH to 15,551 and relogged from there, monitoring Gamma while re-logging to determine if there was proper Gamma layover with Gamma from re-log vs. Gamma from drilling.
 Decision made to TOH by client to change MWD tool at that point.
 Upon reaching surface, motor showed no visible damage, drained well, and had minimal to no squat in bearing section.
 Bit graded 2-2 with 2 plugged jets, broken cutters at nose, 1 broken cutter and wear in matrix at gauge.
POOH for Gamma Failure Motor Prefromed as expected held good diff and drained Good bit was Green

While Sliding Motor Stalled and pressured up @ 175GPM it was at 3600psi. Pressure slowly bled off and we returned to drilling rate. Upon returning to Bottom to start drilling again we werent able to get any diff and ROP was at 7-10 Torque held steady with no spike and decision was made to TOOH. At Surface motor had 1/4 of slack in bearings and did not drain.

The objective of this run was to drill ahead in the Lateral section of the well in the Upper Eagleford.
 BHA thorughout run showed a consistent tendency to build and walk left.
  While on bottom rotating, drilling ahead, we experienced a mini-stall of 800 psi. Shortly thereafter, a sigificant pressure loss took place, going from 5100 off bottom SPP to 4450 SPP. Actions were taken to troubleshoot pressure loss to confirm that it was not above ground. Rubber was seen coming over the shakers at a bottoms up from said pressure loss.
  Client made the decision at that point to backream/TOH with and lay down BHA #7, pick up, make up, and TIH w/ BHA #8.
  Upon reaching surface, motor showed no visible damage, was dry already, and had 1/8 squat in bearing section. 
  Bit graded 3-2 with broken cutters at nose, broken cutters at gauge, and two plugged jets.

After reaming f/15751 t/22545 tagged bottom 3 high due to pipe squat to drill ahead in lateral. After tagging bottom had a diff spike of 780 psi.  Picked up off bottom, got a good zero on diff and weight on bit.  Went back to drilling with 25-35k WOB and 350-400 psi diff.  ROP average was 8 per hour. Instructed driller to pick up and broke over drill string then  go back to bottom trying to relax the drill pipe.  ROP was still averaging 7-10 per hour with 35k WOB and 200 psi diff.  After several attempts to make the BHA drill, decision was made by client to POOH.  Pumped sweep and got some rubber back on bottoms up.  
 Motor drained properly w/ no visual defects.  No slack in the bearings.

AT 05:10 9/16/2022 stalled motor at 795 psi diff and 23k rotary torque.  Killed pumps and picked up off bottom, then went back to 330 gpm losing 300 psi stand pipe pressure.  Set rotary to 40 rpm and picked up to the crack while trouble shooting pressure loss. 
Decision made by client to TOH and call TD at 22,854.
 Upon reaching surface, attempted to drain motor - motor was already dry.No external visible damage at motor, one full inch squat at bearing gap.
 Bit graded 1-2.
BHA performed as expected. Motor drained and had zero to minimal slack in bearing section.  No visual or audbile damage while on surface.
BHA Performed as expected motor drained good

The objective of this run was to kick off and drill Curve section to Intermediate Casing point.
  BHA performed well, achieving excellent build rates. ROP was less than optimal throughout, until a gamma increase and substantial ROP increase occured simultaneously upon reaching the Eagleford target zone.
  Motor drained well upon reaching surface, with no visible damage and 1/4 play at bearing section.
 Bit graded 1-1, in gauge, with the only issue being a noticeably looser bearing at one of the two cones.

No visible damage seen on motor at surface.  1/4 slack seen at bit box.  Assembly held direction well and held angle well while rotating.  Assembly did intermittenly get big pressure spikes while sliding.
Did not get to bottom, washed f/ 15200 to 16880 and gamma failed right before tagging bottom. Inspected motor and bit at surface will rerun.
TROUBLESHOOTING: Recycle

ADDITIONAL_COMMENTS: Motor drained had 1/4 slack, bit was 0,0 will rerun. Motor stalled a few times while rotating but stalled consistently sliding to the point of not being able to slide and get anything out of it. Rop while rotating was still normal for flow rate150-200.

TD well. On surface motor drained good, no prob seen. Axial bearing play was good at .097in. No visual wear observed.  In rotation BHA followed dip and had no walking tendency.  MAX TEMP: 348F.  MTR STALLS & PSI: None.  MOTOR YIELDS: 12-24 deg per 100.  MAX DIFF: 800 psi. AVG DIFF: 350 psi.  BIT: Bit was in guage and had 1 plugged nozzle. Busted cutters in the nose.
No visible damage seen at surface.  Motor drained good.  No slack seen at bit box.  Assembly held angle and direction well.  Assembly was control drilled last 1000 due to gumbo issues.
MWD_COMMENTS: No observed issues during this run, no washed or damged parts

COMMENTS: MWD Failed
ADDITIONAL_COMMENTS: MWD Failed
SURFACEFINDINGS: MWD Tool had no physical damage. Lower End when compressed expelled mud as expected. No wash to tool, Poppet or Muleshoe Sleeve. MWD Tool Failed Surface Tap Test, Flow Test and would not pulse at all. We were able to communicate with the tool and download the memory from the tool so the electronics were still operating, but the pulser was non-functional.
TROUBLESHOOTING: Changed Transducer and Transducer Cable. Attempted different Flow Rates (200-300 GPM). Attempted recycling and working the pipe to jar the MWD Tool. Attempted leaving the pumps off for a few minutes to ensure MWD Tool was shutting off. Changed and Checked Mud Pumps. Issue first happened in the morning around 0500 and the tool began operating as normal so we proceeded to drill ahead. After a few hours of drilling and a few recycles, the tool flatlined and we began troubleshooting again, attempting the same steps as before.
MWD_COMMENTS: Initially the MWD Tool flatlined after drilling out cement, but it came back and was operating as expected. After drilling ahead in the lateral a few hundred feet, the tool flatlined again and did not comeback. After attempting troubleshooting steps the decision was made to POOH for an MWD Failure.

The purpose of this run was to drill out Float equipment/Casing shoe at bottom of Curve, and then proceed to drill ahead in the Lateral section.
  Assembly tracked fairly well, building slightly in rotation, with only two occasions of hard formation push down - both pushes down and left.
  Motor showed no visible damage, no slack at bearing section, and drained well.
 Bit graded 1-2, with broken cutters on gauge.

While TIH w/ Sidetrack assembly, it became necessary to high-side motor at 70? to continue TIH through casing.
  It was necessary to wash and ream to 9,725 due to inability to TIH on elevators. At 9,725, when unscrewing from stump at rig floor, oil-based mud came forth from stump signifying a malfunctioning float valve.
  Decision was made by client to TOH to shoe, and place pressure on the backside in an effort to make the float valve function.
 Soon into the process of TOH wet, we pulled tight, so we screwed into string and engaged pumps to facilitate TOH. At this point we experienced hole packing off, so pumps were killed and we proceeded to backream dry up to shoe. Packing off issue persisted into shoe.
  Decision made by client to TOH all the way. Upon visual inspection, float valve showed to be stuck open due to being obstructed by cement.
  Motor showed no visible damage, drained well, had no significant squat at bearing section.
  Bit graded 1-1.
Motor Performed as expected held good diff and drained good

The purpose of this run was to initiate, perform, and complete Sidetrack procedure, and then continue to drill in new Sidetrack Lateral of well. 
 Upon reaching Sidetrack point at 9,411 MD, we began troughing, and Sidetracked from previous wellbore to continue to drill in new Sidetrack Lateral. 
  While drilling ahead, this assembly showed a consistent tendency to build in rotation in general, with the exception that there were occasions where we would abruptly be pushed hard down and left. Oscillating at end of run while Sliding took roughly 5K Torque.
  Upon reaching surface, motor bit box spun freely at bearing section and was dry, with 1/8 squat.
  Bit graded 1-1.

When P/U Motor bit box would compress to bearing housing and @ TD no slack in bearings. Motor held good and good ROP, While sliding we were limited due to compression of bit box to bearing housing. Motor was dry at surface due to slug.

ADDITIONAL_COMMENTS: While drilling ahead in lateral section @ 19179? ROP started slowing down and differential pressure started coming up slowly to are set point. We reset are bottoms up strokes and started watching shakers and started seeing some rubber on shaker screens. Decision was made to pull out the hole to inspect the BHA. On surface inspection of BHA# 7. We found no visable damage but motor was dry and found on jet stopped up with rubber. Bit graded 1-1,& one plugged jet.

While washing and reaming to bottom at 18532? hole begin to pack off and string became stuck. After working tight hole string was freed. Decision was made to circulate and conditioning well bore clean, then washing and reaming was continued down to 18596?. The hole begins to pack off and string became stuck again. After freeing sting and circulating and conditioning, the pump pressure started increasing and flow was restricted to 150 GPM with 5000 psi. The decision was made to pull out and examine assembly. After back reaming to 18000? with 150 GPM string was able to be pulled on elevators to the base of the curve, where bottoms up was circulated prior to spotting kill mud. While circulating stator rubber was found across shakers. At surface the motor would not drain. When the bit was broken off there were three jets were plugged with stator rubber. The bit graded 1-1-NO-A-X-I-RR-BHA.

While washing and reaming to bottom at 18690? hole begin to pack off and string became stuck. After working tight hole string was freed. Decision was made to circulate and conditioning well bore clean. While circulating and conditioning, the pump pressure started increasing and flow was restricted to 80 GPM with 5000 psi. The pump pressure eventually returned to normal, but at 9300 strokes stator rubber started coming back across shakers. The decision was made to pull out and examine assembly. After back reaming to 18500? the string was able to be pulled on elevators. At surface the motor was drained out before bit was broken off. When the bit was broken off there were two jets were plugged with stator rubber. The bit graded 1-1-NO-A-X-I-RR-BHA.

While drilling surface MWD flatlined at 664 MD. After recycling several times and trying different pumps and pump rates, the decision was made to POOH and replace the MWD probe. Debris was found lodged in the sleeve from a hose cap. MWD probe was replace and new sleeve was installed. The run was completed to TD at surface motor was still tight and bit was 1-1-NO-A-X-I-RR-TD.
MWD_COMMENTS: While drilling surface MWD flatlined at 664 MD. After recycling several times and trying different pumps and pump rates, the decision was made to POOH and replace the MWD probe. Debris was found lodged in the sleeve from a hose cap. MWD probe was replace and new sleeve was installed.

Started reaming to bottom @ 8700 Md. Torque, SPP, and all other parameters were normal. 610 GPM / 3300-3400 SPP / Rotary 40 RPMs Torque 19.5k - 20.5k. After a connection at 10454 MD we seen a little more swing on the torque scale than we had previously. Torque from 19.5k - 24k. Right before the pressure spike Torque jumped to 26k before falling back off at 10488 MD. SPP spiked to 4500 @ 10491 MD. Pressure limit was reached and pumps automatically shut down. Picked up off bottom, cycled pumps and had 4000 psi with 575 GPM. 35 GPM less than previous. While circulating a B/U pressure would instantly increase and then fall back off. Pretty clear we were pushing something through the bit. Bottoms Up samples had several pieces of what appeared to be stator rubber.

Motor drained as normal, very minimal slack in bearing secction. No other visual damage to report. 
Bit jets plugged with rubber.
Bit graded 0-0.
SURFACEFINDINGS: Stator rubber in bit.

ADDITIONAL_COMMENTS:
Upon surface inspection motor drained while setting on mat and had about 3? slack in bearing housing.

While drilling BHA #8 performed well and achieved its objective. BHA was the curve assembly, drilled from 12230 to kick off point at 13451. Then curve was drilled and landed at 14250. Build rates during curve ranged from 6.30* - 12.51* and there were 6 stalls within the first 200 ? 250 feet at differential pressures of 1200psi -1300psi. After landing curve, the BHA continued to drill ,another 1555? in Lateral Section, to 15805? at which time the decision was made to pull out of hole. While drilling in the lateral section BHA #8 seemed to hold direction well and seemed to walk left for the most part. 

Drilled down to 15805, at this depth there was a pressure spike causing the high-pressure limiter on the pumps to kick in. Stall procedure was followed prior picking up. Once off bottom pumps were turned back on, before picking up enough to break over, and pressure came up steady till high-pressure limiter was activated again. At this point drill string was picked up and broke free, pumps were turned back at a decreased rate of 300gpm, and the off-bottom pressure was 100psi ? 200psi high. Went back to bottom and it would no longer drill, just stacked weight. The decision was made to rack a stand back, circulate, and pull out of hole.
TROUBLESHOOTING: Stall procedure was followed prior picking up. Once off bottom pumps were turned back on, before picking up enough to break over, and pressure came up steady till high-pressure limiter was activated again. At this point drill string was picked up and broke free, pumps were turned back at a decreased rate of 300gpm, and the off-bottom pressure was 100psi ? 200psi high. Went back to bottom and it would no longer drill, just stacked weight.

ADDITIONAL_COMMENTS: Tripped In Hole With New Assembly T/14,127. Started Circulating Out Kill Mud W/OBM Once we got Bottoms Up Rubber Started Coming Across Shakers. Decision was made To POOH & Change Out Motor. While POOH string came wet 15 stds before bha which is consistant with previous BHAs. On surface no visible signs of wear.  Bit box was slowly rotating due to hydrostatic which is normal for an oversized power section.  Motor drained normal for being oversized as well.  Axial bearing play from Bico to rerun a 7 motor is 0.259in. Under compression  bearing play was measured at 0.125in which calculates to roughly 65% of bearing life left which is within the limits.  Bit was in guage, cutters looked good and there was no plugged jets. Bit was rerun in BHA 18.  In my opinion for what the motor was used for, which is basically circuluating with no reaming. The bearing play was excessive. I was expecting there to be none.  Being that these motors have very little rubber in them and all the reasons I explained above, in my opinion, there is nothing wrong with the power section.  Max temp seen on run 305?

Determined - May have been something in hole - Tear down report ofmotor displayed nothing wrong. At 13,739? while attempting to slide we tagged bottom getting no differential pressure and no reactive torque. We picked up off bottom zeroed drilling parameters off bottom and rotated the drill string back down with 80rpm easing to bottom putting a total of 30K WOB. The mandrel spun freely, while attempting to break bit off excessive torque was used but was unable to break it off. The bit breaker had to be cut off due to breaker being spun around the bit. We never saw any rubber come back. The decission was made to make a connection and go back to drilling. After we made the connection and brought the pumps back on line, the MWD had flatlined. While drilling ahead at 14,296 MD, we had a pressure spike. After getting off bottom and bringing the pumps back up, the drill string had a lot more pressure. Started tio ciculate at a slower gpm and when we got a bottoms up we found a lot of rubber. Continued to circulate and condition mud to POOH and change out motor. When we had our kill weight mud ready, we went to high side the motor before POOH and the MWD had flatlined. Recycled pumps and still flatlined.

MOTOR_DESCRIPTION: 6/7 8.0 2.12 degree Fixed w/ Stab 6.25 -0.5 OS NBR-HPW
ADDITIONAL_COMMENTS:
While sliding we kept losing 100 psi and losing pulses on MWD. Picked up and lisyened to pumps and nothing was wrong. MWD started pulsing againg so we went back to sliding. After a couple feet we, the MWD flatlined again. The decission was made to POOH.
 On surface it was noticed that the motor was already drained and had 1/2 squat.

When we got back to bottom with this BHA we had an additional 600 lbs of pump pressure. Couldnt find anything possibly wrong on surface. We got good zeros on everything and continued to drill ahead.
While sliding at 17,773 MD we had a pressure spike. We shut the pumps off and picked up and let the torque out. Once off bottom at a neutral wieght we kicked one pump in and the pressure was steady. We then kicked in the second pump and the rotary. After pressure leveled off we had 600 lbs less pump pressure. Made a call and the decission was made to circulate a bottoms up and look for rubber at the shakers, Notified solids control and derrick hand to be ready to look for rubber. They called back and said the cuttings box already had a lot of rubber in it. Motor was chunking for a while. While cieculating bottoms up we went back to bottom and sat 10K on it attempting yo drill and got zero diff.  Decission was made to POOH to change out motor.
When we got to surface there was no external damage to BHA. When the MWD tool was pulled, we noticed the very top stabilizer was completly missing. The whole rubber fin part was gone. As we begain to brake down BHA, we looked on top of the UBHO, Float, and Motor for it. We never found any part of the missing stabilizer. 
Motor did not drain. The bit had one plugged jet and one missing cutter.

TD well this assembly. While we were back reaming out off the hole the motor stalled and the motor started to chunk rubber. When we got out of the hole the motor didnt drain. The bit was missing 3 cutters and had one plugged jet.

COMMENTS: While drilling the curve section at 13,459 we experienced a stall. Immediatley shut the pumps down and bled pressure off. Picked up and broke string free. When bringing pumps back up, the pressure spiked again. Bled pressure off again and brought pumps up. At this point we were about 150 psi light on spp. Tried to go back to bottom and drill with no success. No torque or pressure increase and weight stacked. Upon bottoms up it was observed the the shakers were unloading large amounts of rubber. The decision was made to come out of the hole.Motor was locked up.The mud motor had a total of 37.59 hrs, 21.92 total drilling hours and 15.67 circulating hours. A total of 5.50 hrs of displace and drill out. After the mud motor quit a total of 8.83hrs were circulated while performing bottoms up and pumping kill mud prior to tripping out of the hole.

COMMENTS: While drilling in rotation we experienced a SPP increase of 500psi while drilling ahead rotating. We performed a stall out proceedure but were unable to stabilize pump pressure. We finally got pressure to break over at 6700 psi while surging mud pump strokes. After SPP was stable the rig performed a bottoms up and started backreaming out of the hole. Upon surface inspect motor body appeared to be in good visual condition with 1 .75? of squat, also motor was completely drained when pulled through rotary table. Bit graded at 1-3-BT-S-X-I-PN-BHA  had two plugged jets.

We finally got pressure to break over at 6700 psi while surging mud pump strokes. After SPP was stable the rig performed a bottoms up and started backreaming out of the hole. While sliding pump pressure was lost and it was assumed one pump went down. Picked up and pressure came back but it was discovered there was a pump issue. Swapped pumps and continued sliding. While sliding with 200 to 250psi of differential, pressure started to slowly drop. The rig crew began a check on all surface equipment, but no issues were found. Picked up to connection point and shut down pumps, holding 1,050psi on MPD. Opened the 2? and MPD pressure started to drop. With all troubleshooting done it was determined that the issue was downhole due to a wash out in the pipe. We tripped out of the hole with this mud motor due to washout in drill string.

Drill ahead from 17731 to 17955. While attempting to slide at 17914? a drop of 100psi SPP was noticed. Pumps were shut down and rpm on top drive was brought up to 10 rpm monitoring downhole torque, a possible back out was suspected. Drill string torqued up to 17kftlbs then broke over to 10Kftlbs, at this time pumps were staged up and drill string was pulled to neutral rotating weight of 212K. Then pumps were brought up to full drilling rate of 340gpm, with a new off bottom pressure of 5050psi which was 100psi less. Parameters were monitored till confirmation was received to continue drilling. After rotating 31? all seemed well and another attempt to slide at 17955? was tried. Noticed a 200psi decrease, monitored closely while isolating pipe with a max of 10Kftlbs to the left and 12Kftlbs to the right. Pump pressure began fluctuating by 100psi, it was decided to attempt the same procedure used previously at 17914?.  As off bottom pressure was monitored it slowly declined to 4600psi which was 400 psi less than previous off bottom pressure. At this point the decision was made to weight up to a 17.5ppg before pulling out of hole.Motor was drained once on surface, no visible damage to BHA

Drilling ahead @ 19,735 MD when we got a pressure increase (not a Stall). After making a connection the MWD was having issues getting detection. Leaning the iussue towards the agitator. Once on surface it was noticed that the bit had some missing cutters and chipped cutters. Motor had aabout 1/4 of squat and drained good.

COMMENTS:
Stator Chunked - The objective of this BHA run was to drill out Intermediate casing shoe/float equipment, drill down to kick off point, kick off, drill, and land the curve section, and continue on into Lateral section. Run was successful in reaching this objective.
 Through Curve section, motor yields were low (7 - 10) until roughly 60% into the Curve, at which point motor yields increased substantially (12-14). 
 This BHA did not track as optimally in the Lateral section of the well, walking fairly consistently.While minor walking was common in Lateral with this assembly, no major deviations were seen until Gamma went from 100 to 110, down to the 70s over 45 following a target change to a lower TVD, at which point an almost immediate jump right of 4?/100 to the right was seen. This was corrected by sliding.
  While rotating after connection at 16,810, it was noticed that there was an increase of 200 PSI to off bottom pressure. GPM was then lowered from 333 GPM to 316 GPM due to rig pressure limitations. At depth of 16,928, we experienced a 1,000 PSI motor stall while sliding. After killing pumps and bleeding off Standpipe Pressure, we re-engaged one mud pump. Before, 260 GPM showed 2,200 PSI. After the stall, the PSI at 260 GPM had doubled to 4,400.
  Decision was made by client to POOH and TIH with a new motor and bit. Motor was dry at surface. Bit had 3 of the 6 jets plugged with rubber.

COMMENTS:
MWD Failed - The purpose of this run was to drill out Intermediate Float Equipment/ Shoe, Drill to K.O.P., drill Curve section, and continue on into Lateral section of the well.
 Tool magnetics were out on first attempt at taking a survey with the sensor16 under casing shoe. Every attempt every stand thereafter was also unsuccessful. Troubleshooting included taking a survey in slips to mitigate vibration, as well as recycling at varying flow rates and an attempt to manual downlink with pumps. 
 Decision was made by client to drill ahead to 11,035 and POOH, change out MWD Tool, with the intent to catch any missed surveys while TIH with next run.

COMMENTS:
The purpose of this run was to drill to K.O.P., kick off, drill, and land Curve section, and continue on into Lateral. In this the run was successful.
  Drilling in Curve showed expected build rates throughout. Upon entering the Lateral, BHA showed a tendency to drop in rotation up to the last 1,000 of the run, at which point tendency generally changed to build.
  Upon sliding at 17,746 MD, we experienced an increase of 1,100 PSI. Upon rotating after slide, no more than 100 PSI differential could be attained with putting up to 30K WOB, as well as an increasew in torque to 14K from previous rotation seeing 8K to 10K.
  Decision was made by client at that point to TOH and change BHA.Once on surface motor was locked up bit box Had no play in it.Bearings were gone in Motor,Grade was 2/4 Had 1 plugged jet & 1 missing Jet.

COMMENTS:
The objective of this run was to drill out Intermediate float equipment/casing shoe, drill to kick off point, drill and land curve section, and continue on into lateral section of the well.
  Build rates were as expected for this assembly, with build rates falling off during curve but picking back up by landing. While sliding ahead in the curve section to 11,484,drawworks shut down for over 12 hours. Once drawworks were brought back online and continuing into the curve was possible, sliding was significantly slower than prior to shutdown.
  BHA tracked relatively well in lateral section.
At 19,721, while attempting to slide for inclination, tool faces became less frequent and eventually stopped altogether. At the same time, a 300 psi increase was noticed and remained during circulation before tripping out of the hole.
  Upon reaching surface, motor drained well with no visible damage and minimal play at bearing section.
  Bit grade 3-2, with lost cutters and 2 jets plugged with formation.

ADDITIONAL_COMMENTS: Objective of BHA was to Drill  Lateral Section.While Sliding in Lateral we had build rates from 9-11. After getting back up and running we could only get 310 GPMs with 6000 PSI Off Bottom At that time decision was made to TOOH to change Bit and Motor. While Washing and Reaming to bottom TIH with this assembly, MWD ceased working at 18,218 Reaming Depth, pumping 262 GPM. Decision was made by client to continue TIH to Bottom, and Drill to 20,464, at which point the BHA would be POOH.
 Upon reaching Surface and pulling MWD, the Pulser was found to have broken off at the oilfill. Pulser was still stuck in sleeve in UBHO.
  Motor drained with no slack in bearing section.Bit graded 1-1.

During this run, BHA showed a tendency to drop in rotation.
 At 21,249 MD, MWD tool flatlined during rotation. Troubleshooting consisted of switching mud pumps, changing GPMs, changing out transducer. Attempts to restore communication with MWD tool were unsuccessful.
 Decision made by client to continue drilling ahead to TD of 22,077. 
  At surface, BHA showed no visible damage. Motor drained well with no excess slack in bearing section.
 Bit 1/1 with one missing jet.

Objective of BHA was to Drill Production Vertical to KOP, Drill Curve and Lateral Sections. While Drilling Curve we had Motor Yeilds of 14-16s. While Drilling in lateral BHA tracked well but, wanted to drift to the left. At a depth of 17,615. While Rotating we took a 300 diff spike that caused to rig to hit its pressure limiter and kill the mud pumps. After getting back up and running at full circulating rate there was 1000 psi more off bottom pressure and normal. At that time decision was made to TOOH to change Bit and Motor. At surface Motor drained but had about 1 more of slack that when originally picked up.

 BHA was pulled for ROP. Upon reaching surface, motor drained well with no excess slack a bearing section.

The purpose of this run was to drill in the Intermediate section of the well.
  Initial ROP with this BHA in the Pettit was 120 - 150 FPH. Eventually, 1,000 after entering the Hosston, ROP reduced to 30 to 50 FPH with a corresponding reduction in differential pressure.
  Decision was made by client to POOH due to ROP.
Upon reaching surface, motor showed considerable wear to two stabilizer blades. Motor had no excess slack at bearing section and drained well.
 Bit graded 2-3.

The objective of this run was to drill in the Intemediate section of the well.
  Upon reaching bottom, ROP was low, as was differential. Occasionally ROP would increase to 80/hour and we would see a corresponding increase in differential, but each time it went directly back to low ROP and low differential. Off bottom pressure went from 2250 to 2100 about the same time ROP went from 15/hour to 3/hour.
 Decision was made by client to POOH.
Motor drained briefly and then would drain no more. There was 1/8 play at the bearing section. Bit box could be turned by hand.
 Bit graded 1-2.
BHA Performed Well,No Slack In Motor,Motor Drained Good At Surface,No Visual Signs Of Damage. Bit Grade 1/1

ADDITIONAL_COMMENTS: Drilling ahead in lateral, while sliding @20,729 MD we got a sudden increase in pump pressure. The pumps were brought down and pressure bled off. Then worked string up until it was free and tried to bring pumps up, pressure was still high. Worked stand all the way up and brought pumps online, at first it pressured up and then came back down with about 300 psi less the circulating pressure. The decision was made to come out of the hole after pumping a B/U. At Bottoms the shakers were covered in motor rubber. Once on surface it was noticed that the motor had about 1/8 of squat and locked up. the bit had 4 plugged jets and one jet was missing.

COMMENTS: Hole Issues  The mud motor performed as expected in this section. It was tripped out of the hole after experiencing an increase in torque while rotary drilling. While tripping out of the hole back reaming was performed from 3875? to 2920? due to observed losses. The gpm?s were dropped to 200 at 2930? MD, the hole packed off observing a pressure of 2200psi. At this point drill pipe was worked max pull of 175K with 60-75 rpm?s trapping torque on drill string 22-25 max ft/lbs and surging mud pumps 50-400 gpm?s. After establishing circulation, a freshwater sweep was pumped and increased gpms. The drillstring came free and reamed to 3900? and circulated hole clean. After circulation we tripped out of the hole on elevators to surface. At surface, the mud motor drained fine with minimum bearing play. The kick pad and drill bit had aggressive wear.

COMMENTS: Gamma Distance      Survey Distance
ADDITIONAL_COMMENTS: Rotated with assembly from 10,520 MD to 11,527 MD. Started curve with 300 gpm and immediately notice that the assembly was not acting right, differential was erratic and difficult to hold toolfaces. If trying to get over 600 diff, motor did not want to drill off. Build rates were showing 2?/100, not typical for this assembly. The flow rate was then slowed to 250 gpm and ROP was set to 10/hr. when this was done the differential became more erratic and was jumping from 50 psi to 350 psi. Toolfaces were stil inconsistent. The decision was made to come out of the hole. Once upon surface, there was no visible damage to the motor. No slack in bearings and motor drained strong. There was minimal wear on the bit. Overall investigation was there was nothing externally to contribute the behavior of the BHA and performance.

Suspected motor had shredded the stator , we circulated and looked for rubber at the shakers. Rubber was found before bottoms up. The DE wanted us to go back to bottom and try and drill. After shutting the pumps off, the drill sting held pressure and had to be bled off at the 2. Several attempts where made to pump on the sting but it kept pressuring up. Decission was made to POOH. Attempted to POOH on the elevators but reached max overpull. We had to dry ream out of the hole.

Once out of the hole, the motor had no slack or axial play. We put the bit breaker on and place in the rotary table. The bit box turned and what mud was left in the motor came out of the bit like normal. There was no grinding or popping or unusual sounds or vibration coming from motor while turning bit box. After knock out the float valves it was noticed there was a large plug of LCM and metal that was packed off. There is no way for flow to ge past what was in the float sub.

ADDITIONAL_COMMENTS: BHA Is labed as a motor failure but due to hole conditions. Went in hole with BHA and right outside of shoe we tagged up and took weight. Filled pipe and and rotated slowly to wash thru. Per co. mans orders we added over 100K wod. with all the weight we didnt add any diff or excess torque. WOB fell of erratically. It would go in 20-30 at a time then tag up again. We then would slack off with over 120K WOB and P/U as much as 350K. As we entered curve section where dogglegs were above 9?/100 buildrates they then ordered drill to dry ream down into hole, still with as much as 120K WOB and picking up as much as 350K. While out of hole found the last 8-10 stands of drill pipe scarred up and bit was had several busted cutters. Motor would not drain and bit box would spin freely.

The curve BHA drilled from 10,854 to 11,144 MD using a 2.25 fixed housing motor (6/7 lobe, 8.0 stage) paired with a Diamant SPD613 bit. This assembly was planned to kick off with a build rate of 13/100. Early in the curve, the motor yielded up to 21/100 with good tool face control while holding 800 psi differential and 20k WOB.
At 11,083 MD, five motor stalls were encountered over a 20 interval. Following each stall, tool face was re-established with difficulty. After the stalls, differential dropped to ~500 psi with 810k WOB, and intermittent pressure spikes further impacted tool face control. Build rates had begun to fall off prior to the motor stall interval, down to 9.7, despite consistent slide execution and adequate WOB and differential.
A decision was made to trip out and pick up a more aggressive motor configuration to achieve the required 17.6/100 to land on plan. The assembly was pulled at 11,144 MD (bit depth), with inclination projected at 28.71 at 11,137 MD, short of landing. At surface the motor visually drained fine and did not show any slack in bearings. The bit graded a 1-1 but did have two plugged jets with rubber. The UBHO had to be changed out due to rubber soft rubber in and around the sleeve. It did not appear to be the same rubber in the two plugged jets.

BHA #5 drilled from 11,144 to 11,551 MD as a bailout curve assembly using a Diamant SPD613 bit paired with a 6/7 lobe, 8.0 stage motor set to 2.45 adjustable housing. The assembly picked up building immediately and tracked cleanly to landing.
Early in the run, motor yields averaged ~13.8/100, which was lower than expected based on configuration, which was anticipated to deliver 1820/100. From ~70 inclination onward, build rates improved to 19/100 with stable toolface control. The last survey at 11,456 showed 71.38 INC and 173.22 AZI. The curve was projected to 90.6 INC at 11,551, where the run was called landed. The assembly was pulled for lateral BHA.
Drilling parameters averaged 25k WOB with ROP ranging from 60 to 100 ft/hr. At surface, the motor drained clean with no squat or play observed. Bit graded 1-1
